<h2>Classic Pomodoro (25/5)</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Describe the technique. When to use it: task-based work with clear deliverables, students, writers, people prone to distraction. Link to <a href="/pomodoro/">Timerrapp's Pomodoro timer</a> which automates the full cycle including session tracking. Also mention the <a href="/timer/25-minutes/">25-minute timer</a> for a minimal version.]</p>

<h2>The 52/17 Rule</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Describe the origin (Draugiem Group productivity study). Explain who it's best for: knowledge workers who find 25 minutes too short to reach flow state, but who need more frequent breaks than a 90-minute block allows. How to run it using <a href="/timer/">Timerrapp's timer</a>: set 52 minutes, work, then set 17 minutes for the break.]</p>

<h2>90-Minute Ultradian Blocks</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain the science: the brain cycles through peaks and troughs of alertness roughly every 90 minutes (ultradian rhythm, studied by Nathaniel Kleitman). Working with these cycles rather than against them yields deeper focus. Best for: researchers, programmers, writers doing long-form work. Use the <a href="/timer/90-minutes/">90-minute timer</a> to run a session.]</p>

<h2>Deep Work Sessions</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain Cal Newport's approach: scheduling 2–4 hour blocks with zero interruptions, phone off, notifications disabled. Not a timer-based technique per se, but a scheduled block. The <a href="/timer/1-hour/">1 hour timer</a> or <a href="/timer/90-minutes/">90-minute timer</a> can serve as anchor points within a longer deep work session. Best for: professionals who produce complex intellectual output — researchers, authors, engineers.]</p>

<h2>How to Choose the Right Technique</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Give clear guidance: if you're highly distractible or just starting out → Pomodoro. If you do complex creative or analytical work → 52/17 or ultradian blocks. If you have long uninterrupted mornings and produce high-complexity output → deep work. Suggest experimenting with one technique for a full week before switching.]</p>
